The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Bengal | Briefs
                                                                                                                     4                                                                                      BRIEFS
                  
	Calcutta, July 30: The state Congress today urged the Union home minister to ensure the speedy recovery of illegal arms stockpiled by CPM cadres.    
	State party chief Manas Bhuniya also requested P. Chidambaram to stop the CPM from misusing the joint forces to expand its base. Mamata Banerjee had approached the Prime Minister with the same requests recently.         
	Behrampore: A youth was allegedly hacked to death by the family of a boy who was beaten up by his brother during a game of marbles in a Murshidabad village. The uncle and cousin of Biplab Mondal, 19, were also attacked with sickles and choppers by Bulbul Mondals family.         
	Calcutta: The Left Front on Friday moved a breach of privilege motion against three Trinamul Congress MLAs for trying to stop Speaker Hashim Abdul Halim from going to his chamber after he adjourned the House on Thursday. Halim allowed the motion to be moved but did not accept it because the accused Trinamul MLAs, Bobby Hakim, Arup Biswas and Dibyendu Adhikary, were not present in the Assembly.        
	Santiniketan: Visva-Bharati students will organise a relay hunger strike from Saturday to protest the varsitys failure to announce a rollback of fees hiked recently. However, students wont boycott classes.        
	Calcutta: Maoists on Friday put up posters on one of the gates of Raj Bhavan, slipping through the tight security around the governors residence. The posters, which have been removed, said the rebels were observing a martyrs week to protest the death of six Maoists at the hands of police.                                                                                                                                                      
